  <conclusion xml:id="fs-idp17559008">
    <title>Chapter Review</title>
    <p xml:id="fs-idm56942800">The expected value, or mean, of a discrete random variable predicts the long-term results of a statistical experiment that has been repeated many times. The standard deviation of a probability distribution is used to measure the variability of possible outcomes.</p>
  </conclusion>
  <subsection xml:id="fs-idp161572768">
    <title>Formula Review</title>
    <p xml:id="fs-idm6265952">
      Mean or Expected Value: 
      <m>\mu = \sum_{x \in X} x P(x)</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="fs-idm133403024">
      Standard Deviation: 
      <m>\sigma = \sqrt{\sum_{x \in X} (x-\mu)^{2} P(x)}</m>
    </p>
  </subsection>
