    <exercise xml:id="eip-421">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A student takes a 32-question multiple choice exam, but did not study and randomly guesses each answer. Each question has three possible choices for the answer. Find the probability that the student guesses <term xml:id="term-more-than">more than</term> 75 percent of the questions correctly.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p><em>X</em> = number of questions answered correctly</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p><em>X</em> ~ <em>B</em><m>(\text{32, }\frac{\text{1}}{\text{3}})</m></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>We are interested in MORE THAN 75 percent of 32 questions correct. 75 percent of 32 is 24. We want to find <em>P</em>(<em>x</em> > 24). The event <em>more than 24</em> is the complement of <em>less than or equal to 24</em>.</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Using your calculator's distribution menu: 1 – binomcdf<m>(\text{32, }\frac{\text{1}}{\text{3}},\text{ 24})</m></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p><em>P</em>(<em>x</em> > 24) = 0</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>The probability of getting more than 75 percent of the 32 questions correct when randomly guessing is very small and practically zero.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </solution>
